{"id":"2012.12796","submitter":"Frank Marsiglio","authors":"J.E. Hirsch and F. Marsiglio","title":"Nonstandard superconductivity or no superconductivity in hydrides under\n  high pressure","comments":"11 pages, 13 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 103, 134505 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.103.134505","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Over the past six years, superconductivity at high temperatures has been\nreported in a variety of hydrogen-rich compounds under high pressure. That\nhigh-temperature superconductivity should exist in these materials is expected\naccording to the conventional theory of superconductivity, as shown by detailed\ncalculations. However here we argue that experimental observations rule out\nconventional superconductivity in these materials. Our results indicate that\neither these materials are unconventional superconductors of a novel kind,\nwhich we term `nonstandard superconductors', or alternatively that they are not\nsuperconductors. If the former, we point out that the critical current in these\nmaterials should be five orders of magnitude larger than in standard\nsuperconductors, potentially opening up the way to important technological\napplications. If the latter, which we believe is more likely, we suggest that\nthe signals interpreted as superconductivity are either experimental artifacts\nor they signal other interesting physics but not superconductivity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Dec 2020 16:58:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 2 Apr 2021 18:04:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 6 Apr 2021 19:19:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-04-14"}
